  "text": "The data (volume mixing ratios, VMRs; in nmol mol −1 ) had a temporal resolution of 5 s. Similar to the procedure described by [CITATION_1] , the instrument background (VMR i,instrbgd ), identified in Fig. 2 by the first horizontal gray line (close to zero), was subtracted from the measured volume mixing ratio (VMR i,measured ) for an ion, i at each temperature step according to the following equation: where VMR i is the volume mixing ratio corrected by the background. This calculation was done for all filter samples and all field blanks (FBs). All filter samples were measured three times. From these measurements, the average of the VMR per filter was calculated for each ion i at each temperature step (VMR i ). Note that all VMR i values have been normalized to a N 2 carrier gas flow of 100 mL min −1 .",
